Purpose

The dashboard UI system for Parallel has reached a stable refinement stage.

All major UI refinements have been completed across:

Owner dashboard

Member dashboard

Rotation analysis

Schedule views

Navigation system

Cards and layout system

This rule locks the current UI design system to prevent unintended visual regressions.

Future Cursor changes must respect the current UI structure and styling unless explicitly instructed otherwise.

Scope

This rule applies to all dashboard UI including:

Owner pages

Member pages

Rotation pages

Schedule pages

Team pages

Settings pages

Analysis pages

Shared UI components

Locked UI Principles
1. Owner and Member UI Consistency

Owner and Member dashboards must follow the same visual design language.

They must share:

spacing rhythm

card structure

typography hierarchy

button styles

navigation layout

hover behaviors

pointer interactions

badge styling

stat block styling

Member pages must not fall behind in refinement compared to owner pages.

2. Layout System Is Locked

Dashboard layout structure must remain stable.

Key layout characteristics that must not change:

consistent content width

centered dashboard container

card-based information structure

section spacing hierarchy

visual grouping of components

Do not introduce arbitrary layout changes.

3. Navigation System Is Locked

The product navbar structure is fixed as:

Teams
Rotation
Schedule

Rules:

No additional tabs unless explicitly approved

No visual redesign of the navbar

Active tab indicator must remain consistent

Hover and active states must remain consistent

Landing page demo navigation must match the real product navigation.

4. Component Styling Is Locked

Shared components must retain the current design system:

Buttons

Cards

Inputs

Dropdowns

Tabs

Badges

Modals

Section headers

Do not modify:

border radius

shadow usage

color hierarchy

spacing scale

typography hierarchy

unless explicitly instructed.

5. Cursor Behavior Is Locked

Interactive elements must follow these rules:

Clickable elements
→ cursor-pointer

Drag handles
→ cursor-grab
→ cursor-grabbing while dragging

Non-interactive elements
→ default cursor

Inputs
→ text cursor

Do not introduce inconsistent cursor behaviors.

6. Rotation UI Is Visual Only

Rotation result UI components are visual representations of algorithm output.

Rules:

Do not change:

rotation logic

scheduling logic

fairness scoring

burden distribution

algorithm data structure

UI may display the data but must never modify the algorithm.

7. UI Changes Require Explicit Instruction

Cursor must not refactor UI components proactively.

Avoid:

redesigning layouts

renaming components

restructuring visual hierarchy

changing spacing patterns

unless explicitly instructed.

Allowed Changes

Cursor may:

fix minor visual bugs

fix cursor interaction bugs

fix alignment issues

fix responsive behavior

match Figma UI specifications

improve UI consistency without altering layout structure

Forbidden Changes

Cursor must not:

redesign dashboard layouts

change navigation structure

modify algorithm-related UI logic

alter card architecture

introduce new UI patterns that break consistency

Guiding Principle

Parallel uses a stable dashboard design system.

The UI should evolve carefully and intentionally, not through automated refactors.

When in doubt:

Preserve the existing UI structure.

Relation to Other Rules

This rule complements:

rotation_engine_locked.md

Algorithm logic and UI system are independently locked.

Algorithm stability and UI stability must both be preserved.
